Does your university faculty influence your gaming habits?

Project 2

University of Sydney | 23 Sep 2022

  • 1 Executive Summary
  • 2 Full Report

1 Executive Summary

  • Our project investigates the relationship between an individuals faculty, gaming habits, and sleep.
  • Main findings:
    • There was a weak linear relationship between on campus hours and hours of sleep in a day.
    • Science related subjects appeared to have higher medians than other subjects, regarding the number of hours video games were played in the past week.
    • The top 3 most frequently played video game genres were: Battle Royale, Fighting, and FPS.

2.1.1 Summary

2.1.1.1 Source:

  • The data was obtained from a Google Forms survey which was active from 08/09/2022 to 16/09/2022.

2.1.1.2 Structure:

  • Each column represents a survey question, with 19 variables in total, 6 quantitative and 13 qualitative. The main variables of investigation were:
    • Faculty (qualitative)
    • Number of weeks spent playing games in a month (quantitative)
    • Time spent playing games in the last week (quantitative)
    • Time spent on campus (quantitative).
  • The last 4 columns are optional survey questions included to provide further insight towards gaming habits.
  • Each row represents an individual response to the survey, with a total of 31 responses.
  • Our results demonstrated our sample size was too small for any sufficient data analysis.

2.1.1.3 Limitations:

  • This is a sample survey as only 31 responses were recorded. Not enough data was collected.
  • There is not an equal amount of participants distributed across each faculty, so it would be difficult to pinpoint any differences with accuracy.
  • The survey did not ask for the year or semester the participant is currently studying in.
  • Due to selection bias, only 1 member of staff participated in the survey:
ggplot(survey, aes(x = Are.you.a.student.or.staff.at.the.University.)) +
  geom_bar() +
  xlab("Type of Participant") +
  ylab("Frequency")

  • Possible bias and confounders:
    • Consent bias: participants were able to choose to take part in the study.
    • Selection bias: the survey was spread via social media and ED, thus the participants might consist of like-minded individuals of similar ages and similar preferences.
    • Observational studies: cannot determine causation between investigative variables, only correlation.

2.1.2 Assumptions:

  • It was assumed that participants were ongoing members of staff or students in university.

2.1.3 Data Cleaning:

  • Time of sleep: The data is formatted as AM and PM time in the survey. Although the ability to convert time to an integer or float is possible, R/Studio might see 24 (12PM), as quite far from 1 (1AM) because of how integers are ordered. Hence it was set as an ordered category manually in R.
  • Qualitative Variables: Results for qualitative variables were adjusted so that same responses (e.g.RPG. and RPG) were streamlined so producing graphs was much easier.

2.2 Research Questions

The main research theme for this project was to investigate the relationship between an individuals faculty, gaming habits, and sleep.. To do so, we devised several research questions and produced corresponding graphs in order to determine if the variables had any relationship with each other.

2.2.1 1. Does the time spent on campus due to your faculty affect the amount of time you play games in a week?

  • We can generate a scatter plot for the two quantitative variables:
ggplot(survey, aes(x = Hours_On_Campus, y = Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour = Faculty)) +
  ggtitle("Relationship between time spent on campus and amount of time playing
          video games in a week.") +
  xlab("Time Spent on Campus (hours)") +
  ylab("Amount of Time Playing Video Games in a Week (hours))")

  • We can also calculate the correlation coefficient of the two variables:
cor(survey$Hours_On_Campus, survey$Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game) 
[1] 0.01191024
  • The correlation coefficient of the 2 variables is very low. We can attempt to remove the outlier and calculate the new correlation coefficient:
survey_del =  survey[-22,]
cor(survey_del$Hours_On_Campus, survey_del$Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game)
[1] 0.1864928
  • The correlation is still a very weak positive, albeit higher than with the outlier. We can attempt to fit a linear model to the data, and produce a residual graph:
fit = lm(survey$Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game~ survey$Hours_On_Campus, data = survey)
ggplot(fit, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", colour = "red") +
  ggtitle("Residual vs Fitted.")

  • As can be seen above, the residual plots y-axis is unbalanced and the data is not clustered in the middle of the plot, or distributed evenly. This is not a good residual plot, and suggests our model can be improved much more.
  • We can now produce 2 scatter plots (one with and one without the outlier) to include linear regression:
ggplot(survey, aes(x = Hours_On_Campus , y = Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game))+
  geom_point(aes(colour = Faculty)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  ggtitle("Relationship between time spent on campus and amount of time playing
          video games in a week.") +
  xlab("Time Spent on Campus (hours)") +
  ylab("Amount of Time Playing Video Games in a Week (hours)")


Figure 1. Scatter plot demonstrating relationship between on campus hours and gaming hours. The blue line represents the line of best fit for the data.

ggplot(survey_del, aes(x = Hours_On_Campus , y = Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game))+
  geom_point(aes(colour = Faculty)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  ggtitle("Relationship between time spent on campus and amount of time playing
          video games in a week (outlier removed).") +
  xlab("Time Spent on Campus (hours)") +
  ylab("Amount of Time Playing Video Games in a Week (hours)")


Figure 2. Scatter plot demonstrating relationship between on campus hours and gaming hours but omits an extreme outlier. The blue line represents the line of best fit for the data.

  • As shown in figure 1, there was no linear relationship between the 2 variables. Even when an extreme outlier was removed, there was a very weak linear relationship.
  • This could be due to an insufficient amount of data collected.
  • It seems that individuals who spend more time playing games attend campus less, but this should be further researched.

2.2.2 2. Does your university faculty affect your gaming habits?

  • To investigate this research question, we produced graphs to determine a trend for faculty against the number of weeks video games are played in a month, and faculty against the number of hours video games were played in the last week.
ggplot(survey, aes(x = Faculty)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = Weeks_Last_Month_Played_Videogames)) +
  ggtitle("Relationship between an individual's faculty and their
          gaming habits.") +
  labs(x = "Faculty", y = "Number of People") +
  labs(fill = "Frequency of Playing \nVideo Games") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("0 weeks in a month" = "#FFCEE6",
                               "1 week in a month" = "#FCBCD7",
                               "2 weeks in a month" = "#F9A3CB",
                               "3 weeks in a month" = "#EF87BE",
                               "4 weeks in a month" = "#E56AB3")) +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,margin = margin(0.5, unit = "cm"),vjust =0.5))


Figure 3. Bar plot showing the relationship between an individuals faculty and frequency of playing video games in a month.

# Filter data:

# Engineering 
facultyE = survey$Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game[survey$Faculty == "Engineering"]

# Medicine and Health
facultyM <- survey$Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game[survey$Faculty == "Medicine and Health"]

# Science 
facultyA <- survey$Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game[survey$Faculty == "Science"]

ggplot(survey, aes(x = Hours_A_Week_Playing_Video_Game, y =Faculty,)) +
  geom_boxplot(color="blue", fill="light blue", alpha=0.2) +
  ggtitle("Relationship between Faculty and Time Spent Playing
  Video Games in a Week.") +
  xlab("Time Spent Playing Video Games in a Week (hours)")


Figure 4. Comparative box plot showing the relationship between an individuals faculty and time spent playing video games in a week in hours.

  • Based on figure 3, most individuals from the medicine and health and engineering faculties play video games all 4 weeks in a month.

  • Individuals from the business faculty mostly play video games 1 week in a month.

  • Results for the other faculties may be unreliable due to an insufficient amount of data collected. For example, only one participant of the survey was in the faculty of music.

  • Based on the medians seen in figure 4, it seems that science-related faculties; that is, engineering, science, and medicine and health; play video games more frequently in a week than non-science-related faculties.

  • When observing spread of the box plots, outliers must be considered; the spread for engineering, for example, is quite wide, but this may be due to outliers.

2.2.3 3. How does the amount of time you spend on campus influence the number of hours you sleep at night?

  • We can generate a scatter plot for the two quantitative variables:
ggplot(survey, aes(x = Hours_On_Campus, y = Hours_Of_Sleep)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour = Faculty)) +
  ggtitle("Relationship between time spent on campus and amount of
          sleep.") +
  xlab("Time Spent on Campus (hours)") +
  ylab("Amount of Time Asleep in a Day (hours))")

  • We can also calculate the correlation:
cor(survey$Hours_On_Campus, survey$Hours_Of_Sleep) 
[1] -0.1774387
  • There seems to be a very weak negative correlation between the two variables. We can attempt to fit a linear model to the data, and produce a residual graph:
fitt = lm(survey$Hours_Of_Sleep~ survey$Hours_On_Campus, data = survey)
ggplot(fit, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", colour = "red") +
  ggtitle("Residual vs Fitted.")

  • As can be seen above, the residual plot exhibits a slight level of heteroscedasticity. The model can be improved, but because our sample size is so small, the best solution would be increasing the amount of data collected.
  • We can now produce a scatter plot including linear regression:
ggplot(survey, aes(x = Hours_On_Campus , y = Hours_Of_Sleep))+
  geom_point(aes(colour = Faculty)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  ggtitle("Relationship between time spent on campus and amount of
          sleep.") +
  xlab("Time Spent on Campus (hours)") +
  ylab("Amount of Time Asleep in a Day (hours)")


Figure 5. Scatter plot demonstrating relationship between on campus hours and hours of sleep in a day The blue line represents the line of best fit for the data.

  • Figure 5 demonstrates an attempt at linear regression.
  • It seems that the linear model is not a good fit as the residual plot shows a possible pattern and the correlation coefficient of the two variables is weak.

2.2.4 4. How does your faculty influence the genre of video games you play most?

order_Genre = ordered(survey$Favourite_Game_Genre,
                           levels=c("Battle Royale", "Fighting", "FPS", "Puzzle", "RPG", 
                                    "Sandbox", "Simulation", "Sports", "Strategy", 
                                    "Other", "N/A"))
ggplot(survey, aes(x = Faculty)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = order_Genre)) +
  ggtitle("How does an individual's faculty influence their most played
          video game genre?") +
  labs(x = "Faculty", y = "Number of People") +
  labs(fill = "Video Game Genre") +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,margin = margin(0.5, unit = "cm"),vjust =0.5))


Figure 6. Bar plot demonstrating the relationship between an individuals faculty and their most frequently played video game genre.

  • The top picked favourite genre for games are: Battle Royale, Fighting, and FPS. The participants in the sample seem to favour action-based games, as depicted in figure 7.


2.3 Articles

Previous research found that psychological, technical and media factors could be the cause of gaming habits (Muhamad et al., 2022). Other papers found that education influences gaming habits, as video games are slowly incorporated into teaching plans (Magali, 2008). This is especially relevant in science subjects, as was shown in our results (figure 4).


2.4 References

  • Magali, M. (2008). Students and Video Game Players. SSRN 1302868.
  • Muhamad, M., Muhammad, M. Z., Yunoh, M. N. M., Musa, Z. K. C., Hassan, A. A. M., Abdullah, A. R., & Mohd, F. (2023). The Causation of Online Game Addiction Among University Student. In International Conference on Business and Technology (pp.1025-1033). Springer, Cham.
